When talking about past, in this particular case: PAST PERFECT and SIMPLE PAST we need to have clear how and why we NARRATE and RELATE PAST EVENTS, as well as how and why we SET EVENTS THAT STARTED AND FINISHED IN THE PAST, BUT THEY CAN BE FURTHER or SPECIFIC in the Past. At the end of surfing this source, we will comprehend and apply the differences and contrasts between PAST PERFECT and SIMPLE PAST.

Prerequisite knowledge refers to the knowledge learners should already have in order to be able to effectively complete the learning. Examples of pre-knowledge can be:

  • Learners must be able to assemble standard power tools

Relates to events or actions that started before other one in the past. Therefore, it usually has connection or relation with other event in the past. That is to establish a chronological order or go back to time to mention further or previous events in past.
